WEBVTT

1
00:00:07.416 --> 00:00:08.277
[MUSIC]

2
00:00:08.277 --> 00:00:12.239
A graph or chart uses visual elements
to communicate information about data,

3
00:00:12.239 --> 00:00:13.988
about numbers and related facts.

4
00:00:13.988 --> 00:00:18.534
Just as grammar now owns verbs,
adjectives and other parts of speech,

5
00:00:18.534 --> 00:00:22.494
provides a protocol for
communicating ideas with language.

6
00:00:22.494 --> 00:00:26.094
You can think of a grammar of
graphics as a protocol for

7
00:00:26.094 --> 00:00:29.702
communicating data concepts
with visualizations.

8
00:00:29.702 --> 00:00:34.788
This grammar of graphics, strives to make
visualizations as intuitive as possible.

9
00:00:34.788 --> 00:00:37.762
So anyone looking at
a graphic can quickly and

10
00:00:37.762 --> 00:00:40.978
effortlessly understand
the underlying data.

11
00:00:40.978 --> 00:00:45.787
The grammar of graphics has four basic
layers, starting with the data itself,

12
00:00:45.787 --> 00:00:47.959
followed by aesthetics, scales.

13
00:00:47.959 --> 00:00:51.691
And finally design which
ties everything together.

14
00:00:51.691 --> 00:00:55.522
Let's take a simple example and
see how we can apply this grammar.

15
00:00:55.522 --> 00:01:00.577
Suppose you're an investor tracking
the stock of a particular rocket company.

16
00:01:00.577 --> 00:01:05.033
Your data consists of daily values for
the stocks opening price,

17
00:01:05.033 --> 00:01:09.746
closing price, high value,
low value and volume of shares traded.

18
00:01:09.746 --> 00:01:14.330
To see how things change over time,
you start by creating a graph that his

19
00:01:14.330 --> 00:01:17.805
dates along the X axis and
data values along the Y axis.

20
00:01:17.805 --> 00:01:20.247
You can choose dots as your aesthetic,

21
00:01:20.247 --> 00:01:23.061
with the distance of
each dot from the X axis.

22
00:01:23.061 --> 00:01:28.437
Corresponding to a specific value for
each date, which comprises your scale.

23
00:01:28.437 --> 00:01:32.514
Now, you obviously don't want to
plot everything on the same graph.

24
00:01:32.514 --> 00:01:36.080
It would be too messy to be useful,
even if you applied color or

25
00:01:36.080 --> 00:01:38.833
shape aesthetic to
the different quantities.

26
00:01:38.833 --> 00:01:44.120
So you start by focusing on just one
value, the stock's closing price.

27
00:01:44.120 --> 00:01:48.577
You can easily see how the price went up
sharply toward the end of January and

28
00:01:48.577 --> 00:01:49.798
then quickly drop.

29
00:01:49.798 --> 00:01:53.611
But be careful,
you might miss some useful information.

30
00:01:53.611 --> 00:01:56.782
Adding a visual cue lines
connecting the dots,

31
00:01:56.782 --> 00:02:00.279
reveals an interesting structure,
a double hump.

32
00:02:00.279 --> 00:02:02.377
Now, through intentional design,

33
00:02:02.377 --> 00:02:07.121
you can tell a story that explains more
deeply what the numbers are communicating.

34
00:02:07.121 --> 00:02:11.683
From your experience in the world of
finance, you surmise that the rocket

35
00:02:11.683 --> 00:02:15.891
company's stock price followed
the evolution of an asset bubble.

36
00:02:15.891 --> 00:02:18.768
The similarity between
the rocket company graph and

37
00:02:18.768 --> 00:02:21.322
an example graph depicting
a typical bubble.

38
00:02:21.322 --> 00:02:26.096
Solidifies your conclusion and serves as
a starting point for further analysis.

39
00:02:26.096 --> 00:02:28.865
For instance,
you can develop a new graphic by

40
00:02:28.865 --> 00:02:33.064
looking at additional information
to just the closing price values.

41
00:02:33.064 --> 00:02:36.601
And mapping that data to
a different set of aesthetics.

42
00:02:36.601 --> 00:02:41.368
For each date, you can use a thin vertical
line to represent the range of high and

43
00:02:41.368 --> 00:02:42.519
low stock prices.

44
00:02:42.519 --> 00:02:46.215
The days volatility and
bars placed on top of the vertical lines

45
00:02:46.215 --> 00:02:50.063
to indicate the difference between
opening and closing prices.

46
00:02:50.063 --> 00:02:54.094
Blue bars indicate that the stock
closed higher than it opened and

47
00:02:54.094 --> 00:02:56.595
red bars indicate that it closed lower.

48
00:02:56.595 --> 00:03:01.318
Thus the addition of the new aesthetics
reveals that opening prices were mostly

49
00:03:01.318 --> 00:03:03.088
higher than closing prices.

50
00:03:03.088 --> 00:03:07.435
And that the run up to the spike,
came along with very high volatility,

51
00:03:07.435 --> 00:03:09.911
a narrative is beginning to take shape.

52
00:03:09.911 --> 00:03:13.406
Finally, you can apply some
statistical analysis to the data,

53
00:03:13.406 --> 00:03:16.656
such as calculating the rolling
volatility for each date.

54
00:03:16.656 --> 00:03:21.186
And plotting it as a shaded area on
top of the closing price graph line.

55
00:03:21.186 --> 00:03:23.840
The combination of this derived
quantity with raw data,

56
00:03:23.840 --> 00:03:26.946
further develops your insight
into what happened historically.